	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Towards a Pacific regional FPA?</h1>

			
			<h4>
												04 September 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The fourth Pacific ACP consultation meeting on new trading options with the EU was held in Honiara (Solomon Islands) at the end of April 2005. The objectives of the meeting were to consider issues in relation to the on-going preparations for phase II of the EPA negotiations and to consider and formulate negotiating positions on a number of important sectors including fisheries.</p><p>On fisheries issues, there was support for negotiating a multilateral fisheries agreement given that it addressed development issues. This would include, among other things, the capacity to establish, harvest and process the product of fisheries and also the capacity to meet quality standards.</p><p>This echoes the results of a sustainability impact assessment study of EPAs published in February 2005 by PriceWaterhouseCoopers, in which EU-Pacific fisheries relations were discussed. This IAS demonstrated that the existing EU-Pacific bilateral tuna-fisheries agreements (BFAs) with Kiribati, the Solomon Islands and the Federal States of Micronesia, based on access fees, do not promote economic, environmental or social sustainability. The report noted that: ‘The access fees granted to the EU fleet under the BFAs do not contribute significantly to GDP in the PACP countries because they are relatively modest, monitoring is weak, much of the fish caught is not landed, and where fish is landed, there is little capacity to process it and add value’.</p><p>Moreover, the IAS reported that ‘Lax enforcement of fisheries agreements, low capacity by the PACP countries to monitor catches and private arrangements between EU ship-owners and local officials to enter the coastal zones of the countries threaten the viability of the artisanal fishery in the long term. As ‘most of the processing units’ supply comes from the small-scale fisheries ... maintaining the health of the artisanal fishery is key for the PACP countries’. The IAS also argues that ‘from an environmental perspective, the system of access fees under the BFAs acts as an incentive to encourage over-fishing of all stocks, including tuna. Moreover, there is no accountability attached to the financial contributions that accompany the access fees, and targeted towards fisheries conservation’.</p><p>A regional FPA between the EU and the PACP countries, negotiated in the context of the EPA, is the scenario promoted by the IAS. It concludes ‘An FPA that promotes sustainable fisheries and de-links financial contributions from access to the fishery is likely to be both compatible with the WTO and an effective mechanism for promoting good governance in the fisheries sector’.</p>
		
		
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The ‘multilateral fisheries agreement approach’, dealing on the one side, with access to ACP resources by EU fleets, and on the other side, with ACP development issues such as fish processing, access to EU market, etc is gaining increasing support amongst ACP countries.</p><p>As the EU is building up its presence in the Pacific Ocean to take advantage of a Convention on the conservation and management of highly migratory fish stocks in the western central Pacific Ocean (WCPTC), it is important for Pacific nations to take such a position on their future fisheries relations with the EU.</p><p>This position in favour of a ‘multilateral fisheries agreement approach’ is also being promoted by COMESA and is also being discussed at the level of the sub-regional fisheries committee for west Africa. The EU, until now, has refused to envisage the negotiation of a multilateral agreement, on the basis that their mandate does not allow for such a multilateral negotiation. That may be one more reason for reviewing their negotiating mandate.</p><p>In any case, the building up of a common and harmonised approach amongst ACP countries for their future fisheries relations with the EU can only be beneficial, particularly in cases where the EU’s interests include access to migratory species such as tuna.</p>
		</div>
		
